Durch das langsame Garziehen im Ofen passiert das nicht, weil die Temperatur extrem niedrig ist. Das im Fleisch enthaltene Eiweiß verändert die Struktur erst ab 64 Grad. Daher ist es wichtig, dass der Backofen beim Garen des Fleisches eine konstante Temperatur hat, die nicht höher als 60 Grad ist. Durch die lange und niedrige Temperatur kann sich der Fleischsaft in Ruhe verteilen. Das Steak wird stressfrei zart. Slow cooking in the oven prevents this, due to the extremely low temperature. The proteins within the meat begin to alter their structure only at temperatures above 64 degrees Celsius. Therefore, it's crucial that the oven maintains a steady temperature no higher than 60 degrees Celsius while cooking the meat. The long and low temperature allows the meat juices to distribute evenly. The steak becomes tender without any stress. When monitoring the temperature, one should not depend solely on the oven's dial but use an oven thermometer instead. Most ovens are inaccurate at temperatures below 100 degrees Celsius.

Der Drehort in der Wüste führte zu einem Kakerlakenbefall, der während der Produktion sehr problematisch wurde. Diese Probleme verzögerten die Dreharbeiten um sechs Monate und führten dazu, dass das Budget über Bord ging.

The smog was so thick that it affected half of the crew during filming, as well as Moctezumas revenge (intense diarrhea), which affected the cast and crew. Francesca Annis almost died when she accidentally set off a gas oven and was hospitalized for weeks. These problems delayed filming by six months and caused the budget to go overboard.

Grundsätzlich hast du auf der Gitarre dafür erst einmal die Töne zur Hand (bzw. am Hals), die du eh schon greifst. Ähnlich wie in der Theorie oben gibt dir dein Akkord also vor, welche Töne am einfachsten zu deinem Akkord passen. Allein ist es aber schon schwerer, sowohl den Rhythmus als auch die Melodie zu spielen. Hier kannst du zum Beispiel (lernen) die Akkorde anzuschlagen, und dann im Laufe des Taktes einzelne Saiten aus dem Akkord zu picken. data.translation: So, you've got your chord progressions down. You've also devised a strumming rhythm, and now you're looking to layer in a melody. Generally, when playing the guitar, you already have access to the notes on the fretboard where you're forming chords. Just as the previous theory discussed, your chord naturally suggests which notes will harmonize best with it. Nonetheless, managing both the rhythm and melody simultaneously can be quite tricky. Here, you might learn to strum the chords and gradually pluck individual strings within the chord throughout the measure. By doing so, you invariably highlight the melodic note hidden in the chord, while weaving the remaining notes into a cohesive melody.

Er entwickelte durch systematisches Variieren von Parametern einige Techniken zum bildgebenden Verfahren von Klängen, welche uns weit über die Grenzen einer rein materialistischen Weltanschauung verweisen. Jenny veröffentlichte insg. 2 Bücher (1967 und 1972), die heute in einem Band, Kymatik – Wellenphänomene und Schwingungen, zusammengefasst wurden. Das Wort Kymatik selbst, ist aus dem altgriechischen Wort κῦμα, von Welle abgeleitet. Der obige Originalfilm aus den 60er Jahren von Dr. Hanns Jenny, Cymatics – Bring Matter to Life with Sound, zeigt deutlich die beeindruckende Welt der Kymatik mit faszinierenden Bildern und Experimenten.
data.translation: The term Cymatics was coined in the 1960s by the Swiss physician and natural scientist Dr. Hans Jenny. He used it to summarize all phenomena that occur when sound and vibration meet matter. By systematically varying parameters, he developed some techniques for imaging sounds, which go far beyond the boundaries of a purely materialistic worldview. Jenny published a total of 2 books (in 1967 and 1972), which have now been combined in one volume, Cymatics – Wave Phenomena and Vibrations. The word Cymatics itself is derived from the ancient Greek word κῦμα, meaning wave. The above original film from the 1960s by Dr. Hanns Jenny, Cymatics – Bring Matter to Life with Sound, clearly shows the impressive world of cymatics with fascinating images and experiments.

data.text: Es kam zu einer Fusion aus englischer Folk Music, Skiffle, Blues, Rock and Roll, Gospel, teilweise auch Jazz und Klassik, die eine vollkommen neue Musikrichtung hervorbrachte, die auf dem Blues basierte, aber viel variantenreicher war: Erst der (Merseyside) Beat, dann der Rock. Allein die Beatles hatten eine unglaubliche stilistische Vielfalt und eröffneten damit ein extrem breites Spektrum, in dem sich andere Bands verorten konnten. Die Stones waren stärker dem Blues und dem Rock and Roll verhaftet, schufen aber einen rockigeren Sound, auch durch Einsatz von Verzerrern. John Mayall begründete mit seinen Bluesbreakers den Blues-Rock, und sein Gitarrist Eric Clapton entwickelte den rocktypischen Gitarrensound mit Sustain und Verzerrung, indem er den Röhrenverstärker zum Entsetzen der Tontechniker übersteuerte. Und dann kam Jimi Hendrix…
data.translation: It came to a fusion of English folk music, skiffle, blues, rock and roll, gospel, partially also jazz and classical, which gave birth to a completely new genre of music based on the blues, but much more varied: first the (Merseyside) beat, then the rock. The Beatles alone had an incredible stylistic diversity and thus opened up an extremely broad spectrum in which other bands could locate themselves. The Stones were more rooted in the blues and rock and roll, but created a rockier sound, also through the use of distortions. John Mayall established blues-rock with his Bluesbreakers, and his guitarist Eric Clapton developed the typical rock guitar sound with sustain and distortion by overpowering the tube amplifier to the horror of sound engineers. data.translation: Among the wind instruments, both brass and wood, the oboe appears to be the most challenging to master. The double reed, manipulated by the lips and held in the mouth, is particularly tricky to control, especially when producing high notes right from the initial overblow. Achieving the full range of the double horn, as with the bass clarinet, also demands years of practice. Nonetheless, producing the initial controlled tones is somewhat easier on these instruments than on the oboe. A significant additional challenge with the oboe is the need for high air pressure combined with a restricted airflow. While most wind players quickly learn to inhale anew, oboists must also exhale beforehand, a task difficult to accomplish quietly and one that consumes precious time.

data.translation: All instruments have their challenges, and none of them are really easy to learn. What is particularly difficult for someone may vary individually. Whether it's the hand position on the harp, the finger placement on the piano, the plucking of the (classical) guitar, the precise gripping on the mandolin, the tremolo of strings, the bowing of a string including direction changes, lip control on brass instruments, or the mastery of the almost countless instruments of the percussionist, it is probably difficult to predict. One might think that hitting a timpani is simple, but it's probably never been tried by someone who considers it easy. Ok, tone is simple. Loudness, timbre, intonation, tuning, the exact moment of the "sound" etc. are more than enough variables to struggle with.

data.translation: Every musical instrument presents its own set of challenges, and none can be considered truly easy to master. The aspects of playing that individuals find particularly difficult vary widely. Whether it’s maintaining the correct hand posture on a harph, positioning the fingers on a piano, plucking a classical guitar, achieving precise fretting on a mandolin, executing a string tremolo or mastering directional changes in bowing, managing lip control for brass instruments, or mastering the vast array of percussion instruments cannot easily be predicted. Anyone who thinks striking a timpani is simple has likely never attempted it. Granted, producing a tone might be straightforward. However, managing volume, tone quality, intonation, tuning, and pinpointing the precise moment to create the sound are more than enough challenges to overwhelm anyone.

data.text: Als Student sowohl der Anthropologie als auch der Biologie kann ich dir sagen, dass der Planet der Hüte eine verdammt dumme Idee ist. Weder eine Gesellschaft noch eine Spezies kann erfolgreich genug sein, um einen Planeten zu beherrschen, ohne generalistisch und vielfältig zu sein. Nehmen wir zum Beispiel die Grosskatzen - alle Grosskatzen sind obligate Fleischfresser (können nur Fleisch essen, im Gegensatz zu z.B. Hunden, die etwas Gemüse verdauen können), so dass sie alle spezialisierte Raubtiere sind. Aber diese spezialisierten Raubtiere sind äußerst anpassungsfähig und können als einsame Raubtiere aus dem Hinterhalt, als Rudeljäger oder sogar als Aasfresser überleben, und sie sind in der Lage, Jagd auf eine Reihe von Tieren zu machen, von winzigen Nagetieren bis hin zu großen Pflanzenfressern.
data.translation: As a student of both anthropology and biology, I can tell you that the idea of a Planet of Hats is pretty ludicrous. Neither a society nor a species can be successful enough to dominate a planet without being generalist and diverse. Take big cats as an example - all big cats are obligate carnivores (they can only eat meat, unlike dogs, who can digest some vegetables), so they are all specialized predators. However, these specialized predators are highly adaptable and can survive as solitary ambush predators, as pack hunters, or even as scavengers, and they are capable of hunting a range of prey, from tiny rodents to large herbivores.

data.text: In ihren letzten Stunden legte ich sie in ein weiches Nest auf dem Tisch. Ich hielt ihr mit dem Finger Frischkäse hin, den sie mit ihrer kleinen Zunge von meinem Finger leckte. Ich danke dir, das du mein Leben begleitet hast. Ich danke dir, das du mir Kinder geschenkt hast. Kleine Mausi.“ In dem Moment ließ sie meine Fingerkuppe los, rollte sich etwas zur Seite und starb.
data.translation: In her final moments, I gently placed her in a cozy nest on the table. I offered her a taste of fresh cheese on my finger, which she delicately licked with her tiny tongue. She adored fresh cheese. She remained lying on her side for three hours. I noticed that her arm was tucked under her chest and I carefully repositioned it. Suddenly, she clutched the tip of my finger with her small hand and held onto it tightly for just over a minute. I whispered to her, "It's time for you to go now. Thank you for being a part of my life's journey. Thank you for giving me children, my little Mausi." In that moment, she released my finger, shifted slightly, and peacefully passed away.
